"Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Nanhoran Issa, Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"About 1440–About 1489":"about 1440–about 1489","1440–1469":"1440–1469","1460–1535":"1460–1535","1440–1489":"1440–1489","1469":"1469","1535":"1535","1489":"1489","About 1489":"about 1489","1440":"1440","1460":"1460","About 1440":"about 1440","Lleyn, Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Lleyn, Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Banbury, Oxfordshire, England":"Banbury, Oxfordshire, England","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Nanhoran Issa, Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Howel","type":"LAST","meanings":["The English form of the Welsh name Hywel."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Howel Vychan was born about 1440, in Lleyn, Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Rhys ap Dafydd Llwyd. She died about 1489, in Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 51."},"et":{"About 1440–About 1489":"umbes 1440–umbes 1489","1440–1469":"1440–1469","1460–1535":"1460–1535","1440–1489":"1440–1489","1469":"1469","1535":"1535","1489":"1489","About 1489":"umbes 1489","1440":"1440","1460":"1460","About 1440":"umbes 1440","Lleyn, Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Lleyn, Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Banbury, Oxfordshire, England":"Banbury, Oxfordshire, England","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Nanhoran Issa, Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"About 1440–About 1489":"noin 1440–noin 1489","1440–1469":"1440–1469","1460–1535":"1460–1535","1440–1489":"1440–1489","1469":"1469","1535":"1535","1489":"1489","About 1489":"noin 1489","1440":"1440","1460":"